properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued January 4 at 1:10PM CST until January 5 at 12:00PM CST by NWS Mobile AL
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents.

* WHERE...In Alabama, Mobile Coastal and Baldwin Coastal
Counties. In Florida, Escambia Coastal, Santa Rosa Coastal and
Okaloosa Coastal Counties.

* WHEN...Through Thursday morning.

* IMPACTS...Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and
localized beach erosion. Rip currents can sweep even the best
swimmers away from shore into deeper water.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Surf heights have dropped to below advisory
criteria based on observations and beach reports, thus the High
Surf Advisory has been cancelled. The HIGH rip current risk
remains in effect through tomorrow morning.
properties.instruction:
Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued January 4 at 5:00AM CST by NWS Mobile AL
properties.description:
At 500 AM CST, National Weather Service doppler radar indicated
strong thunderstorms along a line extending from 3 miles south of I65
And AL 113 to 4 miles south of Orange Beach. Movement was east at 55
mph.

HAZARD...Winds in excess of 40 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor damage to outdoor objects is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Ferry Pass, Brent, West Pensacola, Wright, Fort Walton Beach, Ensley,
Warrington, Crestview, Niceville, Gonzalez, Destin, Andalusia, Eglin
AFB, Pace, Milton, Opp, Valparaiso, Brewton, Orange Beach and Mary
Esther.
properties.instruction:
If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 1100 AM CST for south central
and southwestern Alabama...and northwestern Florida.

properties.areaDesc: Monroe; Conecuh; Butler; Escambia; Covington; Mobile Inland; Baldwin Inland; Mobile Central; Baldwin Central; Mobile Coastal; Baldwin Coastal; Escambia Inland; Escambia Coastal; Santa Rosa Inland; Santa Rosa Coastal; Okaloosa Inland
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued January 4 at 4:02AM CST by NWS Mobile AL
properties.description:
At 401 AM CST, National Weather Service doppler radar indicated
strong thunderstorms along a line extending from I65 And AL 113 to 5
miles east of I65 And AL 225 to near Prichard to near Coden. Movement
was northeast at 50 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 50 mph and penny size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor damage to outdoor objects is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Midtown Mobile, Downtown Mobile, Prichard, Ferry Pass, Brent, West
Pensacola, Ensley, Tillmans Corner, Warrington, Saraland, Gonzalez,
Bay Minette, Atmore, Foley, Pace, Milton, Monroeville, Theodore,
Chickasaw and Satsuma.
properties.instruction:
If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 1100 AM CST for south central
and southwestern Alabama...and northwestern Florida.
